# hexa-lang /.roadmap — created 2026-04-26
# Re-introduced after 2026-04-25 retire (commit 3caebc54). Scope is
# narrow on purpose: hexa-lang-internal compiler/runtime work that
# does not belong in hive's SSOT. Cross-repo coordination still flows
# through hive/.roadmap.
#
# Ω-saturation cycle (raw 37/38/39/43 — hive SSOT) is the default mode
# for this file. Every active entry below carries an `omega-stop <type>`
# field naming the physical/mathematical limit-witness that terminates
# the retry loop; absence of that field implies `omega-saturation-exempt
# <reason>`. Single-shot or fixed-iteration implementation is forbidden:
# every entry's `attempts` log records the convergence trajectory.

# scope
#   hexa-lang = self-hosted compiler + runtime + stdlib.
#   This file tracks compiler/runtime ROI work; agent/UX/swarm work
#   belongs in hive. Per-repo SSOT files were retired 2026-04-25 in
#   favor of hive-as-sole-source, but compiler-internal initiatives
#   (toolchain, codegen backends, perf wedges) accumulated locally
#   without a registry — this file restores that registry only for
#   hexa-lang-internal scope.

# baseline (2026-04-26, post perf-32 + 02af1622 + 132d1e17 + 5401409e)
#   tool/changelog_parse.hexa cold aot_build_slot profile (16KB flat):
#     module_loader flatten   215ms   7%
#     hexa_v2 transpile        26ms   1%   (was 2,192ms pre-02af1622)
#     clang -O2 link        1,600ms  84%  ← dominant
#     other                  ~250ms   8%
#   hexa_full.hexa (753KB) transpile: 631ms.
#   codegen_c2.hexa (280KB) transpile: 147ms.
#   Conclusion: clang link is the bottleneck on every cold compile and
#   every runtime.c edit invalidation. README claims "Self-hosted 100%
#   .hexa" but the AOT path is hexa → C → clang → native, anchored on
#   an external C compiler.

# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TERMINAL GOAL — Ω: clang 완전 해소 (zero external C-compiler)
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Move the AOT pipeline from
#     .hexa → hexa_v2 → .c → clang → native exe
# to
#     .hexa → hexa frontend → IR → self/codegen/* → ELF/Mach-O exe
# with NO external cc, ld, or as on the path.
#
# This is hexa-lang's true self-hosting goal: the README claim becomes
# truthful only when the C-substrate intermediary is gone. SH1..SH5
# below are wedges along that convergence path; the terminal entry
# [SH-Ω] declares the fixpoint the cycle is iterated toward.
#
# Vocabulary (raw 37 limit-witness types):
#   physical:     bekenstein landauer compute-saturation memory-saturation
#                 energy-saturation
#   mathematical: categorical-limit kolmogorov-incomputability
#                 solomonoff-incomputability fixpoint-convergence
#                 banach-fixpoint lawvere-fixpoint
# Enforcement layer (raw 43): hive-agent (this registry) + os-level
# (chflags uchg + git history); advisory drop forbidden without
# enforce-layer-rationale.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# active entries — each carries an omega-stop field; attempts log
# below the status block records the convergence trajectory.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- partial [SH1] AOT cc dispatch surface (wedge: faster cc swap)
  omega-stop compute-saturation
  rationale-stop:
    clang is already LLVM-tuned for the hexa-emitted 12K-LOC C TU
    shape. Single-cc substitution (zig cc / tcc / gcc) saturates the
    same LLVM cost surface; ≥30% wall-clock gain is unreachable from
    cc-swap alone. Witness: zig cc on hexa-generated C is no faster
    than clang on the same input, despite zig's separate frontend.
  scope:
    Add HEXA_AOT_CC env toggle in aot_build_slot Layer-3 link step
    so non-clang backends can be swapped in without code edits and
    the link cache invalidates cleanly across backends. Default
    "clang" preserves baseline (zero regression).
  acceptance:
    - HEXA_AOT_CC=clang behaves byte-identical to pre-W1 binary
    - HEXA_AOT_CC=<other-cc> routes through new backend with the
      link cache key folding the backend identity (no stale exe)
    - 0 perf regression on default path
  attempts:
    1 (2026-04-26, commit 3921d4c9): clang→zig cc swap.
      result: trivial cold 3.17s clang vs 5.49s zig cc;
      changelog_parse 5.57s vs 6.24s; blocker_autofire 5.72s vs
      6.60s. zig cc no faster on hexa-emitted C TU. Bench machine
      load avg 11+ — variance ±50% same-binary same-cache. Reliable
      ≥30% measurement requires load <2.
      next: stop iterating cc-swap; escalate to SH2 (TU split) and
      SH3 (frontend bridge) for real wins.
    2 (next, conditional): only re-enter if a future cc emerges
      with a fundamentally different cost shape (e.g. a
      hexa-source-aware backend that skips C entirely — that's
      really SH3, not SH1).
  blockers:
    - none for SH1's narrowed scope (dispatch surface only)
  related:
    - SH2 (real perf via TU split)
    - SH3 (real self-host via native bridge)

- todo [SH2] runtime.c TU split + cached runtime.o
  omega-stop banach-fixpoint
  rationale-stop:
    runtime.o is a content-addressable artifact of (runtime.c
    content × cflags × uname). Once cached per key, subsequent
    builds at the same key are O(1) lookup. The cache is a
    contraction map on the build state space; iteration converges
    to the cached blob in one step. fixpoint = stable cached .o.
  scope:
    Stop codegen_c2.hexa from emitting `#include "runtime.c"`.
    Replace with `#include "runtime.h"` (extern decl surface).
    Pre-compile runtime.c → runtime.o once per (cflag, uname)
    tuple; cache under .hexa-cache/_layers/runtime_o/<key>.o.
    Link script.o against cached runtime.o instead of recompiling
    11K LOC of runtime per script.
  acceptance:
    - cold aot_build_slot ≥30% faster on changelog_parse.hexa under
      quiet load (load avg <2)
    - byte / behaviour identical exe output vs current pipeline
    - runtime.c content change invalidates the cache (covered by
      src_fingerprint_deep already)
    - first-build cost (one runtime.o compile) amortizes across all
      future scripts on same machine
  attempts:
    1 (next): blocker phase — runtime.h extraction. Either auto-
      generate from runtime.c via cproto/clang -ast-dump or hand-
      curate the public-symbol surface. measure surface size.
    2: codegen_c2.hexa emit-pattern change (smallest possible diff;
      preserve all existing tests).
    3: main.hexa link step split (1-shot clang → cc -c + cc link).
      reuse SH1 dispatch surface for the link tool.
    4: bench under quiet load; verify ≥30% gate; if missed, escalate
      to compile-only TU shrink (further codegen_c2 changes).
  blockers:
    - runtime.h extraction (no existing artifact; first attempt cost)
    - codegen_c2 emit pattern (touches a hot file; coordinate with
      any ongoing SH1/SH3 work)
    - quiet bench environment (load <2) — current Mac is at 11+
  related:
    - SH1 dispatch surface (HEXA_AOT_CC reused for cc -c step)
    - Agent 3 132d1e17 layered cache pattern

- todo [SH3] hexa-source → IR frontend bridge (real self-host wedge)
  omega-stop fixpoint-convergence
  rationale-stop:
    The hexa language surface is finite but evolving. The frontend
    bridge converges when every node-kind hexa_v2 emits has either
    (a) a native-IR lowering or (b) an explicit fallback-to-clang
    gate. The set of node-kinds is closed in the AST schema and
    monotone — each landed lowering is permanent. Fixpoint = every
    node-kind handled (either native or fallback-gated), at which
    point clang fallback usage measures the residual non-native
    surface. Convergence is iterative across phases; each phase
    closes one node-kind family.
  scope:
    Build the missing piece between hexa_v2's AST shape (used by
    codegen_c2.hexa to emit C) and compile_pipeline.hexa's IRInstr
    /IRBlock shape (used by ir_to_arm64 / codegen_native to emit
    machine code). Once bridged, a phase ladder graduates more
    node-kinds onto the native path; everything else falls back
    to clang via SH1 dispatch surface (zero regression).
  acceptance:
    - trivial println("hi") cold compile fully self-hosted under
      HEXA_AOT_CC=native: no clang, no as, no ld on the path
    - ≥30% faster than W0 baseline on quiet load for the supported
      subset
    - automatic fallback to clang for unsupported nodes (changelog
      _parse / blocker_autofire keep working — zero regression)
    - HEXA_AOT_CC=native dispatches through the bridge; default
      remains clang (changing the default is a separate decision)
  attempts:
    1.A (2026-04-26, recon): AST schema comparison done.
      finding: hexa_v2 emits AST as map-tree (HexaVal map per node;
        codegen_c2.hexa:6095 fn emit_hxi(ast, src_bytes) consumes
        it). codegen_native.hexa uses flat Node[] + index pointers
        (struct Node {kind, int_val, op, name, l, r, e}; helpers
        n_int/n_var/n_bin/n_call/n_let/n_if/n_while/n_fn/n_return).
        Two schemas are conceptually isomorphic but representationally
        different. codegen_native lacks a StringLit node entirely
        (build_string_demo emits raw bytecode for "42").
      adapter shortlist (~300-400 LOC for opt-1 trivial subset):
        opt-1 hexa_v2-AST → codegen_native-Node[] converter (preferred:
          stable hexa_v2 AST, reuses 6/6-pass codegen_native demo
          path, scales to phases 2-6).
        opt-2 new hexa_v2 → IR backend (codegen_c2 sibling, ~500-700
          LOC; reuses compile_pipeline IR optimizations).
        opt-3 mini-parser bypassing hexa_v2 (~150-200 LOC, scale-
          forbidden — not picking).
      next: 1.B verify hexa_v2 binary actually exposes AST externally
        (or whether codegen_c2.hexa is invoked in-process with AST
        in memory). If hexa_v2 is opaque, bridge must run in the
        same process as hexa_v2 — i.e. as part of self/main.hexa
        cmd_run, not as a separate post-process tool.
    1.B (2026-04-26, recon): hexa_v2 binary AST exposure check.
      finding-1: hexa_v2 binary is opaque. CLI surface is
        `hexa-cc <input.hexa> <output.c>` only. No --dump-ast or
        --emit-ir option. AST stays in-process; binary outputs C.
      finding-2: hexa_cc.c is a regenerated artifact (header line
        1 says `regenerated via hexa cc --regen`); the four
        authoritative source modules are hexa scripts:
          self/lexer.hexa        ( 35 KB)  fn tokenize(source)
          self/parser.hexa       (186 KB)  fn parse(tokens) → ast
          self/type_checker.hexa ( 65 KB)
          self/codegen_c2.hexa   (280 KB)  fn emit_hxi(ast, src_bytes)
      finding-3: this means the bridge can run IN-PROCESS as a
        hexa script — `use self/lexer; use self/parser; use
        self/codegen_native;` — without spawning hexa_v2 or
        modifying hexa_cc.c (artifact, regenerable). Resolves the
        "AST exposure" blocker entirely.
      finding-4: AST shape verified by probing /tmp/probe_ast.hexa.
        AstNode is a Map (#{ "kind", "name", "value", "op", "left",
        "right", "cond", "then_body", "else_body", "params", "body",
        "args", "fields", "items", "variants", "arms", "iter_expr",
        "ret_type", "target", "trait_name", "methods" }). Empty
        fields are "" or []. parse() returns an array of top-level
        statements. `println("hi")` becomes:
          [ ExprStmt { left: Call {
                left: Ident { name: "println" },
                args: [ StringLit { value: "hi" } ]
            } } ]
      finding-5: cold cost of lexer+parser import is ~10s user
        (ad-hoc probe). One-time per cold compile; subsequent
        hits within a session warm via AOT cache. Acceptable for
        first prototype; optimize if needed.
      next: 1.C — write self/ast_bridge.hexa for the trivial
        subset (ExprStmt/Call/Ident/StringLit/IntLit). Skip the
        bridge for any node-kind not in the subset and surface a
        "fallback to clang" error so aot_build_slot can route
        accordingly.
    1.C (2026-04-26, MVP done): tool/aot_native_trivial.hexa
      shipped (90 LOC). Pattern-matches a single-statement
      `println("<lit>")` AST and dispatches to
      codegen_native.build_string_demo() to emit ARM64 Mach-O
