      import — 27s user, 4min wall — and polluting downstream
      callers).
      witness check (Ω-saturation pattern):
        - clang procs during build: 0 (verified via
          `pgrep -f clang | wc -l` before/during/after).
        - native binary produced (34864 bytes Mach-O, runs rc=0).
      caveat: produced binary prints "42" regardless of the input
      string literal, because build_string_demo's bytecode is
      hardcoded. Functional correctness ("hi" → "hi") is 1.D.
      timing: ~33s wall cold (lexer.hexa+parser.hexa import), no
      AOT cache for the bridge yet. perf vs clang baseline
      meaningless until 1.D + caching land.
      next: 1.D — dynamic string passthrough so the binary prints
        the actual literal. Approach: keep build_macho_hex header
        layout, build the code_u32 array dynamically using
        codegen_native's enc_movz/enc_str_sp helpers + svc(0x80).
        Pattern: stack-resident string (movz/movk to load up to 8
        ASCII bytes into x0, str x0,[sp,#-16]!, then sys_write(1,
        sp, len) + sys_exit(0)).
    1.D (2026-04-26, code shipped — measurement deferred):
      build_println_dyn(s) added to self/codegen_native.hexa (~50
      LOC). Packs s + '\n' (≤ 8 bytes total) into a 64-bit word
      via 1 movz + up to 3 movk into x3, sub sp/str x3, sys_write
