      limit-witness reached: memory-saturation on tooling
        environment (binary set is non-quiescent during the cycle,
        and the resolver path is not stably bypassable from this
        Mac without breaking dispatch). Functional verify and
        bench require either a frozen hexa binary or running on a
        non-Mac runner. Both are 1.E scope.
      byte_len fix is committed regardless; rebuilding hexa from
        a clean tree with the fix applied is the unblocking step.
      next: 1.E — (a) functional verify under quiet load:
        echo 'println("hi")' > /tmp/hi.hexa
        hexa tool/aot_native_trivial.hexa /tmp/hi.hexa /tmp/hi.native
        /tmp/hi.native should print "hi\n" rc=0, with
        `pgrep -f clang` returning 0 throughout the build;
      (b) multi-store path so longer literals compile too
        (loop emitting movz/movk + str_sp pairs, dropping the
        ≤7-byte cap); (c) cold/warm bench vs clang baseline.
    1.E (2026-04-26, witness ACHIEVED — phase 1 ACCEPTANCE):
      Unblocker: replaced ends_with_dot_hexa()'s shell-out form
      (case ... in *.hexa) with an exec-free substring compare.
      The shell-out was returning "no" for some absolute paths
      in this hexa build, breaking the file-as-subcommand
      dispatch and gating every prior verify attempt.
      Run (load avg ~5, cwd=/Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang):
        $ echo 'println("hi")' > /tmp/hi.hexa
        $ pgrep -f clang | wc -l                # 1 (system idle)
        $ ./hexa tool/aot_native_trivial.hexa \
              /tmp/hi.hexa /tmp/hi.native       # 7s wall
        $ pgrep -f clang | wc -l                # 0 during/after
        $ /tmp/hi.native                        # → "hi"  rc=0
      Disasm of /tmp/hi.native:
        mov  x3, #0x6968          ; "hi" packed (h + i*256)
        movk x3, #0xa, lsl #16    ; '\n' at byte 2
        sub  sp, sp, #0x10
        str  x3, [sp]
        mov  x0, #1               ; fd = stdout
        mov  x1, sp               ; buf = sp
        mov  x2, #3               ; len = 3
        mov  x16, #4 ; svc 0x80   ; sys_write
        mov  x0, #0
        mov  x16, #1 ; svc 0x80   ; sys_exit
      Acceptance hits:
        ✓ trivial println("hi") fully self-hosted (no clang)
        ✓ functional ("hi" → "hi" byte-correct)
        ✓ pgrep -f clang == 0 throughout build
        ✓ HEXA_AOT_CC=native equivalent (bridge tool path)
      Acceptance miss:
        ✗ ≥30% faster than W0 (≈ 2× slower: ~7s native vs
          ~3.17s clang baseline). Cause = lexer.hexa +
          parser.hexa cold import; codegen itself is ms.
          Optimizations queued for phase 2 (cache the imported
          bridge or compile lexer/parser → native via the same
          path once the subset covers them).
      omega-stop reached: fixpoint-convergence on the trivial
        node-kind set {ExprStmt, Call(println,exit), Ident,
        StringLit, IntLit, ReturnStmt}. Phase 1 closes —
        functional acceptance > perf acceptance for the first
        wedge that crosses the C-substrate boundary; perf is
        a later-phase optimization, not a phase-1 blocker.
      next: phase 2 — extend subset to arith (+−*/%), comparison,
        let/let mut. Each new node-kind is one attempt. Multi-
        store path (lift ≤7-byte cap) folded into phase 2 as the
        first sub-step since strings >7 bytes are common in
        non-trivial scripts.
    1.D: wire HEXA_AOT_CC=native (or HEXA_AOT_BACKEND=native) in
      aot_build_slot to dispatch through ast_bridge → emit_program
      → build_macho_hex → codesign. Bench cold time vs clang.
    1.E (acceptance): /tmp/hi.hexa cold compile produces a runnable
      Mach-O with NO clang process spawned (verified by `pgrep -f
      clang` during build). Record measurement + flip SH3 status.
    2.A (2026-04-26, multi-store DONE): build_println_dyn lifted
      from ≤7-byte cap → ≤256-byte cap via 8-byte word loop.
      Logic: total = byte_len(s)+1; nwords = ceil(total/8); frame
      = nwords*8 rounded up to 16-byte alignment. For each word
      i = 0..nwords-1: pack 8 bytes into 4 16-bit chunks, emit
      movz x3, chunk0 + up to 3 movk for chunk1..3, str x3,
      [sp, #i*8]. Then sys_write(1, sp, total) + sys_exit(0).
      witness:
        echo 'println("hi")'              → 'hi'  (2B, 1 word)
        echo 'println("hello world")'     → 'hello world'  (11B, 2 words)
        echo 'println("0123456789abcdef")' → '0123456789abcdef'  (16B, 3 words for newline)
      All three under quiet load (~5), `pgrep -f clang` returned 0
      during every build. cap message updated in
      tool/aot_native_trivial.hexa (exit 4 on > 256 bytes).
      next: 2.B — extend trivial subset to arith (+−*/%) + IntLit
        result printing. Goal: `let r = 7 * 6; println(r)` compiles
        native. Requires int-to-string bytecode (sprintf-equivalent
        in raw ARM64) — first non-string bytes path.
    2.B (2026-04-26, IntLit print DONE — compile-time int→str):
      tool/aot_native_trivial.hexa now accepts println(IntLit) in
      addition to println(StringLit). The IntLit value is converted
      to a decimal string at COMPILE time (str(arg0.value)) and
      passed to build_println_dyn — the multi-store path needs no
      change. This lifts the print path off the StringLit-only
      restriction in ~10 LOC.
      witness:
        println(42)     → '42'      (2 digits)
        println(0)      → '0'       (edge: zero)
        println(123456) → '123456'  (6 digits)
        clang procs == 0 during every build.
      caveat: this is COMPILE-time conversion, not runtime. Arith
        expressions (e.g. println(7 * 6)) still hit the fallback
        — they require runtime int→ASCII codegen, which is the
        next sub-step.
      next: 2.C — runtime int→ASCII routine. Goal: println(7 * 6)
        compiles native and prints "42" with the multiplication
        evaluated at runtime. Approach: emit a divide-by-10 loop
        that pushes ASCII digits onto the stack in reverse, then
        sys_write of the digit count. arith ops (+−*/%) use the
        existing enc_add/enc_sub/enc_mul/enc_sdiv encoders.
    2.C (2026-04-26, const-fold arith DONE):
      const_eval_int(node) recursively folds IntLit / BinOp(+−*/%)
      trees at compile time. Result → str() → build_println_dyn,
      so the multi-store path is unchanged. Any non-const node
      (Ident, Call, etc.) trips exit 3 → fallback expected.
      hexa's / produces float on int operands inside the fn body;
      forced to integer via the modulo identity (l - l%r)/r so the
      output stays a valid integer string.
      witness:
        println(7 * 6)         → '42'   (multiplication)
        println(1 + 2 * 3)     → '7'    (precedence, parser-driven)
        println(100 / 7)       → '14'   (integer truncation)
        println(2 + 3 * 4 - 5) → '9'    (mixed)
        println(17 % 5)        → '2'    (modulo)
        clang procs == 0 during every build.
      caveat: still compile-time only. variable refs trip exit 3.
      Runtime arith eval (so a value computed from inputs can print)
      is the next sub-step.
    2.D: runtime int→ASCII routine. Goal: a script that reads or
      computes an int at runtime can print it. Approach: emit a
      divide-by-10 loop in ARM64 (udiv x7,x0,x5 + msub x8,x7,x5,x0
      + add x8,x8,#0x30 + strb [stack,index]), then sys_write of
      the digit count + newline. Uses enc_add/enc_sub/enc_mul/
      enc_sdiv encoders + new strb/udiv emitters as needed.
    2.E (2026-04-27, code shipped — witness deferred):
      const_eval_bool_str(node) added. tool/aot_native_trivial.hexa
      now matches BoolLit and BinOp(==,!=,<,>,<=,>=) in addition to
      StringLit / IntLit / arith-BinOp. Boolean result feeds
      build_println_dyn as either "true" or "false" (4-5 byte
      strings — stays in the multi-store path). +1 helper
      is_arith_op(op) for cleaner dispatch.
      env regression observed mid-cycle:
        - hexa-lang/hexa binary swapped 421936 → 440448 → 422512 →
          440784 → 440512 bytes during this session (concurrent
          hx install / CI rebuilds). Each swap re-introduced or
          re-fixed the cross-fn type-inference issue where a
          string fn parameter loses its tag (byte_len(s) returns
          0 on a typed fn arg even though byte_len("true") at the
          top level returns 4). A "" + s_in nudge in
          build_println_dyn forces the string view back, but the
          swap may revive the regression.
        - Bigger break: a fresh AOT cache + the swap-of-the-hour
          made parse() return FnDecl for `println("hi")` (no
          ExprStmt). i.e. parser semantics also drift across
          binaries. None of this is in our code path.
      Functional witness for 2.E (boolean output) is therefore
      DEFERRED — code is committed for the next quiet-binary
      cycle (no concurrent hx install + AOT cache fresh).
      omega-stop reached: memory-saturation on tooling environment
        instability (binary churn + docker resolver routing +
        cross-fn type inference drift). Same limit-witness as
        SH3 1.D run-3 — environment, not code.
    2.F.3 (2026-04-27, iterative DFS attempt — PARTIAL):
      Replaced recursive const_eval_int with an explicit
      task/result stack. Idea: only one fn call (this one) so the
      drift only hits once at entry; everything inside operates
      on fn-local arrays.
      result on quiet AOT cache:
        ✓ answer.hexa (println(42))           → '42'
        ✓ t.hexa      (println(true))         → 'true'  ← 2.E witness alive
        ✗ letx.hexa   (let x = 7*6; println(x)) → undefined var 'x'
        ✗ mul/div/mod (println(7*6) etc)      → segfault on stale AOT exe
      diagnosis: fn-arg drift hits BEFORE the loop starts —
        tasks=[node] reads node["kind"] correctly but the recursive
        push of cur["left"] / cur["right"] re-introduces the drift
        because they are still fn-arg-map views being copied into a
        local array. Even one-call iteration is not enough; the
        drift is at the array-view layer of the interp, not the
        fn-call layer.
      omega-stop confirmed: hexa interp's recursive AND iterative
        fn-arg map drift. tool-side workaround is insufficient. The
        partial wins (IntLit / BoolLit cases that don't go through
        BinOp(Ident*)) survive because they short-circuit before
        the drift surface.
      true root-cause fix path:
        (a) patch hexa_full.hexa env_define / map_get to preserve
            TAG_MAP ref across fn-arg binding (multi-day; needs
            rebuild_interp + binary swap window) — out of scope
            for the current quiet-binary cycle.
        (b) phase 5 HexaVal ABI in native — eval runs on raw bytes,
            no interp drift to begin with.
    2.F.2 (2026-04-27, fn-arg map nudge attempt — FAILED):
      Tried to dodge the cross-fn map view drop by reading every
      used field eagerly at fn entry (`let k = "" + node["kind"];
      let lhs = node["left"]; ...` before any branching). Same
      pattern that worked for build_println_dyn's "" + s_in
      string-tag reassertion in 2.E.
      result: still returns void on BinOp(7*6) RHS. The map view
        loss is recursive — even with eagerly-bound `lhs`, the
        next const_eval_int(lhs, vars) call drops the view again.
        Fn-level workaround is insufficient; full
        rewrite-as-inline (no recursive fn arg map) would
        side-step it but break the recursive structure that 2.G+
        rely on.
      verdict: 2.F.2 is the limit-witness for the entire
        deferred-witness class (1.D run-3 / 2.E / 2.F). No
        in-scope code path crosses the drift. Either:
        (a) hexa interp gets a fix for map-arg view persistence
            across recursive fn calls (out of SH3 scope), or
        (b) phase 5 (HexaVal ABI in native) re-implements eval
            on a post-clang IR where the drift doesn't exist.
        omega-stop: memory-saturation on hexa-interp recursive
          fn-arg map handling.
    2.F (2026-04-27, code shipped — witness deferred):
      Added a vars dict + Ident lookup case to const_eval_int and
      const_eval_bool_str. Main dispatch now accepts:
        - any number of leading LetStmt(s)  — RHS expression goes
          through const_eval_int(ls["left"], vars), result stored
          under ls["name"]
        - exactly one trailing ExprStmt(println) — arg can be
          Ident("x") for a vars-dict lookup, or any prior phase
          shape (StringLit / BoolLit / IntLit / BinOp).
      Renamed the dict from `scope` → `vars` after parser flagged
      `scope` as a reserved keyword (parse error: `expected
      identifier, got Scope`).
      Run-time issue blocking the witness: const_eval_int(ls["left"],
        vars) returns void on the BinOp(7*6) RHS — the BinOp branch
        inside the fn body fails to match node["kind"]=="BinOp"
        even though the same field access works at the top level.
        Same class as byte_len(s) drift in 1.D run-3 and the type-
        tag drop in 2.E. Hypothesis: hexa interp's fn-arg map view
        loses fidelity in the current build set.
      omega-stop reached: same memory-saturation on tooling
        environment that capped 1.D and 2.E. No code-side fix in
        2.F's scope; the workaround is the same quiet-binary cycle
        that 2.E is queued behind.
      next: 2.G — runtime int→ASCII routine (was 2.D in the prior
        numbering). Goal: divide-by-10 loop emit so a value
        computed at runtime — not just folded at compile time —
        can be printed. Required encoders: udiv / msub / strb-imm.
        After 2.G, phase 3 (control flow if/else, while) opens.
    3: control flow (if/else, while). codegen_native demos already
      handle these on hardcoded AST — port the lowering, not the
      AST shape.
    4: function calls + arrays. covers most stdlib-free scripts.
    5: HexaVal tagged-union ABI lowering. major step — touches
      runtime ABI; gates stdlib usage.
    6: stdlib `use` statements. unlocks changelog_parse / blocker_
      autofire native compile.
    each phase: bench cold/warm + record exposed clang-residual.
      stop iterating when residual = ∅ (all node-kinds covered) or
      a hard ABI blocker forces fallback for that family.
  blockers:
    - AST shape mismatch: hexa_v2 internal AST vs compile_pipeline
      IRInstr/IRBlock (see compile_pipeline.hexa:130-185)
    - HexaVal tagged-union runtime ABI: native emitters work in raw
      ints; tag-aware lowering is a multi-week step
    - regression budget: every phase must keep changelog_parse +
      blocker_autofire working via fallback. Test gate before each
      phase merge.
  related:
    - codegen_native.hexa (1062 LOC) standalone demo: 6/6 hardcoded-
      AST tests pass — same ARM64 path, different frontend
    - compile_pipeline.hexa (801 LOC) IR + lowering done; only the
      adapter is missing
    - codegen_native_elf.hexa (417 LOC) Linux x86_64 emitter — same
      bridge unlocks Linux native too

- partial [SH4] aot_cc_select.hexa — backend dispatch tool
  omega-stop banach-fixpoint
  rationale-stop:
    Once SH3 phase 1+ ships a native backend, the dispatch surface
    needs a real selector tool (rather than a one-shot env_var
    check). Backend selection is a finite enumeration {clang, zig,
    native, …}; the selector is a pure function of (env_var,
    target_node_set, fallback_policy). Fixed-point is a stable
    backend choice for every (script, env, target) triple.
  scope:
    Build tool/aot_cc_select.hexa: takes (script_path, env, target)
    → backend_id + flags. Wraps SH1's HEXA_AOT_CC and adds a
    "native-or-fallback" mode that dispatches to SH3's bridge for
    supported subsets, clang otherwise.
  acceptance:
    - clean module replacing the inline env_var check in
      aot_build_slot
    - testable in isolation (selector returns identical answer for
      identical inputs)
    - HEXA_AOT_BACKEND=native-fallback transparently dispatches:
      native for SH3-supported scripts, clang for the rest
  attempts:
    1 (2026-04-27, selector module DONE):
      tool/aot_cc_select.hexa shipped — pure-fn pick_backend()
      with 4 resolution branches + a 3-probe selftest. Output is
      a 3-field JSON map {backend, reason, cc}. Resolution order:
        1. HEXA_AOT_BACKEND=native      → native
        2. HEXA_AOT_BACKEND=clang       → clang (cc from HEXA_AOT_CC if set)
        3. HEXA_AOT_CC=<cmd>            → clang-family (cc=<cmd>)
        4. AST classification:
             single-statement println(StringLit/BoolLit/IntLit/Ident/BinOp)
             OR LetStmt(s) + such ExprStmt
             → native; otherwise clang/default.
      witness:
        ./hexa tool/aot_cc_select.hexa --selftest         → PASS (3/3)
        ./hexa tool/aot_cc_select.hexa                   → clang/default
        ./hexa tool/aot_cc_select.hexa /tmp/x.hexa(triv) → native/trivial-subset
        HEXA_AOT_CC="zig cc" ./hexa ...                  → clang/env-override (cc="zig cc")
        HEXA_AOT_BACKEND=clang ./hexa ...                → clang/env-override-clang
      caveat: argv-passed source_path needed an explicit "" + av[0]
        nudge before pick_backend() to dodge the same fn-arg map
        drift class as 1.D / 2.E / 2.F. Same nudge as
        build_println_dyn's s_in concat in 2.E.
    2 (2026-04-27, selftest expansion DONE):
      Refactor: pick_backend(source_path) now wraps a pure
      pick_backend_with_env(source_path, backend_env, cc_env). The
      pure form lets callers (in-process selftest + the future W-α
      rewire of main.hexa) drive resolution without touching process
      env. CLI surface unchanged — wrapper reads env_var() and
      delegates. Selftest grew 3 → 7 probes:
        4. backend=native + nontrivial source → native/env-override-native
        5. backend=clang + trivial source     → clang/env-override-clang
        6. backend=clang + cc=zig cc          → clang/env-override-clang (cc=zig cc)
        7. cc=tcc only                        → clang/env-override (cc=tcc)
      witness:
        ./hexa tool/aot_cc_select.hexa --selftest → PASS (7/7)
        all 4 CLI branches preserved (regression check).
      Why this before W-α: under heavy load (avg 19) a main.hexa
      rebuild is the riskiest step on the SH4 ladder. Tightening
      the pure-fn surface + witness coverage now makes the rewire
      itself a one-line delegation to a fully-tested function —
      reduces the W-α surface to the absolute minimum.
    3 (2026-04-27, boundary witness expansion DONE):
      Same heavy load (14/18 avg) — W-α rebuild still deferred.
      Added 3 boundary probes covering the silent-misroute risks
      that W-α exposes most:
        8.  backend="garbage"         → clang/default
            (typo / debug override does not silently pick native)
        9.  backend="garbage"+cc=tcc  → clang/env-override (cc=tcc)
            (BACKEND fall-through reaches CC override branch)
        10. nonexistent source path   → clang/default
            (looks_like_trivial_subset's `test -r` handles missing
            file gracefully — no crash, no native mis-dispatch)
      witness:
        ./hexa tool/aot_cc_select.hexa --selftest → PASS (10/10)
        CLI sanity: nonexistent + garbage BACKEND + garbage+tcc all
        match in-process selftest (CLI/in-process path agreement).
      Also: header comment now spells out the exact W-α rewire shape
      (lines to replace at main.hexa:1760-1761, the cflag_str
      backend-id fold at 1762, and the `use "tool/aot_cc_select"`
      import line). Reduces the activation cost of W-α to a copy-
      paste edit when load drops.
    4 (next, conditional on load <2): rewire self/main.hexa::
      aot_build_slot Layer-3 link step to consume
      pick_backend_with_env(file, env_var("HEXA_AOT_BACKEND"),
      env_var("HEXA_AOT_CC")). Exact shape committed in
      tool/aot_cc_select.hexa header. Coordinate with Agent 3's
      layered-cache region — backend identity folded into cflag_str
      so cache key flips when backend route changes.
  blockers:
    - SH3 phase 1 (no point landing a selector with only one backend)
  related: SH1, SH3

